{
  "The longest division of the geologic time scale is the:": "",
  "Mesozoic Era, particularly regarding": "",
  "Precambrian (Hadean, Archean, and Proterozoic eons)": "",
  "Paleozoic Era, particularly regarding": "",
  "Cenozoic Era, particularly regarding": "",
  "The Precambrian spans from Earth's formation approximately 4.6 billion years ago to 541 million years ago, encompassing about 88% of all geological time and three separate eons.": "",
  "The Cambrian Explosion occurred at the beginning of which era?": "",
  "Precambrian": "",
  "Paleozoic": "",
  "Mesozoic": "",
  "Cenozoic": "",
  "The Cambrian Explosion approximately 541 million years ago marks the beginning of the Paleozoic Era and the Phanerozoic Eon, when most major animal phyla appeared in a geologically rapid burst of diversification.": "",
  "From largest to smallest, the hierarchy of geologic time divisions is:": "",
  "Era, Eon, Epoch, Period": "",
  "Eon, Era, Period, Epoch": "",
  "Period, Epoch, Eon, Era": "",
  "Epoch, Period, Era, Eon": "",
  "The geologic time scale is organized from largest to smallest divisions as Eon, Era, Period, and Epoch, with each level subdividing the one above it into smaller, more specific time intervals.": "",
  "Earth is approximately how old?": "",
  "6,000 years": "",
  "4.6 billion years": "",
  "100 billion years": "",
  "1 million years": "",
  "Radiometric dating of meteorites and the oldest minerals on Earth indicates our planet formed approximately 4.6 billion years ago from the solar nebula, along with the rest of the solar system.": "",
  "The Cenozoic Era is known as the age of:": "",
  "Mammals": "",
  "Dinosaurs": "",
  "Trilobites": "",
  "Fish": "",
  "Following the extinction of non-avian dinosaurs at the end of the Cretaceous, mammals diversified rapidly to fill vacant ecological niches, making the Cenozoic Era the Age of Mammals.": "",
  "Era boundaries on the geologic time scale are typically defined by:": "",
  "Major mass extinction events": "",
  "Changes in Earth's orbital parameters": "",
  "Continental movements": "",
  "Changes in rock color": "",
  "The boundaries between the three Phanerozoic eras correspond to the largest mass extinction events in Earth's history, which dramatically changed the composition of life and left clear markers in the fossil record.": "",
  "We currently live in which period and era?": "",
  "Permian Period, Paleozoic Era": "",
  "Quaternary Period, Cenozoic Era": "",
  "Jurassic Period, Mesozoic Era": "",
  "Cretaceous Period, Mesozoic Era": "",
  "We live in the Quaternary Period of the Cenozoic Era, specifically in the Holocene Epoch, which began approximately 11,700 years ago at the end of the last ice age.": "",
  "The Mesozoic Era ended approximately 66 million years ago due to:": "",
  "Continental drift alone": "",
  "A massive flood event": "",
  "Gradual cooling over millions of years": "",
  "An asteroid impact and associated climate disruption": "",
  "The Mesozoic Era ended with the Cretaceous-Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction event approximately 66 million years ago, triggered by the Chicxulub asteroid impact and possibly compounded by Deccan Traps volcanism.": "",
  "The Phanerozoic Eon began approximately how many million years ago?": "",
  "1,000 million years ago": "",
  "250 million years ago": "",
  "541 million years ago": "",
  "100 million years ago": "",
  "The Phanerozoic Eon, whose name means 'visible life,' began approximately 541 million years ago with the Cambrian Explosion, marking the first appearance of abundant, complex animal life in the fossil record.": "",
  "During most of the Precambrian, life was limited to:": "",
  "No life existed at all": "",
  "Complex animals and plants": "",
  "Dinosaurs and early mammals": "",
  "Single-celled organisms and later simple multicellular life": "",
  "For most of the Precambrian, life consisted primarily of single-celled organisms like bacteria and archaea, with simple multicellular organisms appearing only in the last few hundred million years before the Cambrian Explosion.": "",
  "What is the Paleozoic Era?": "",
  "The era dominated by dinosaurs from 252 to 66 million years ago": "",
  "The current era in which mammals dominate": "",
  "The time before any life existed on Earth": "",
  "The era of ancient life spanning from 541 to 252 million years ago, featuring fish, amphibians, early reptiles, and massive forests": "",
  "The Paleozoic Era (meaning 'ancient life') spans from 541 to 252 million years ago and witnessed the evolution of fish, amphibians, reptiles, insects, and the first land plants and forests.": "",
  "What is the Mesozoic Era?": "",
  "The era of early single-celled life forms": "",
  "The era of ice ages and glaciation": "",
  "The era of middle life spanning from 252 to 66 million years ago, dominated by dinosaurs and also called the Age of Reptiles": "",
  "The era when mammals first appeared and became dominant": "",
  "The Mesozoic Era (meaning 'middle life') lasted from 252 to 66 million years ago and is divided into the Triassic, Jurassic, and Cretaceous periods, during which dinosaurs dominated terrestrial ecosystems.": "",
  "What is the Cenozoic Era?": "",
  "The era before complex life evolved, particularly regarding extinction under the given assumptions": "",
  "The era of ancient marine life, particularly regarding cenozoic under the given assumptions": "",
  "The most recent era spanning from 66 million years ago to the present, characterized by the diversification and dominance of mammals": "",
  "The era of dinosaur dominance, particularly regarding present under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "The Cenozoic Era (meaning 'recent life') began 66 million years ago after the extinction of non-avian dinosaurs and continues to the present, during which mammals, birds, and flowering plants diversified to dominate global ecosystems.": "",
  "What is an eon in the geologic time scale?": "",
  "The largest division of geologic time, spanning hundreds of millions to billions of years": "",
  "A subdivision of a period": "",
  "The smallest division of geologic time": "",
  "A unit of time equal to exactly one million years": "",
  "An eon is the largest unit of geological time, with Earth's history divided into four eons: Hadean, Archean, Proterozoic, and Phanerozoic, each spanning hundreds of millions to over two billion years.": "",
  "What does the term 'Phanerozoic' mean?": "",
  "Hidden life, referring to microscopic organisms": "",
  "Visible life, referring to the eon when abundant, complex life became visible in the fossil record": "",
  "No life, referring to a period before organisms existed": "",
  "Ancient rock, referring to the oldest rocks on Earth": "",
  "Phanerozoic literally means 'visible life' in Greek, and this eon begins at 541 million years ago when complex, hard-shelled organisms first appeared abundantly in the fossil record during the Cambrian Explosion.": "",
  "What does 'Cambrian Explosion' mean?": "",
  "The explosion of a star that triggered the formation of Earth": "",
  "The geologically rapid appearance of most major animal body plans (phyla) in the fossil record approximately 541 million years ago": "",
  "A mass extinction event that ended the Cambrian Period": "",
  "A volcanic super-eruption that occurred during the Cambrian Period": "",
  "The Cambrian Explosion refers to the geologically sudden appearance of most major animal phyla in the fossil record over a period of roughly 20 to 25 million years, representing the most dramatic diversification of complex life in Earth's history.": "",
  "What is a geologic period?": "",
  "The largest division of geologic time": "",
  "A unit of time equal to exactly one billion years": "",
  "The time between two volcanic eruptions": "",
  "A subdivision of an era, typically lasting tens of millions of years and defined by distinctive fossil assemblages": "",
  "A geologic period is a subdivision of an era, typically lasting tens of millions of years, and is defined by characteristic fossil assemblages and rock sequences, such as the Jurassic, Cretaceous, and Quaternary periods.": "",
  "What is a geologic epoch?": "",
  "The largest division of the geologic time scale": "",
  "A period of exactly one million years": "",
  "Another name for a geologic era": "",
  "A subdivision of a period, representing the smallest commonly used unit of geologic time": "",
  "An epoch is a subdivision of a geologic period and represents the finest commonly used division of the geologic time scale, such as the Holocene Epoch (the current epoch) or the Pleistocene Epoch (the Ice Age epoch).": "",
  "What does the term 'Precambrian' mean?": "",
  "The time after the Cambrian Period": "",
  "The vast span of geologic time before the Cambrian Period, encompassing roughly 88% of Earth's history": "",
  "The era when dinosaurs first appeared": "",
  "A specific 100-million-year period of volcanic activity": "",
  "The Precambrian is an informal term for all of geologic time before the Cambrian Period, spanning from Earth's formation at 4.6 billion years ago to 541 million years ago, covering approximately 4 billion years.": "",
  "What does 'mass extinction' mean in the context of the geologic time scale?": "",
  "The extinction of only one species at a time": "",
  "A geologically rapid event in which a large percentage of Earth's species go extinct, often marking boundaries between eras or periods": "",
  "The normal background rate of species going extinct one at a time": "",
  "The gradual evolution of new species replacing old ones": "",
  "A mass extinction is a catastrophic event in which 75% or more of all species disappear in a geologically short time, and these events serve as the primary markers defining the boundaries between major divisions of the geologic time scale.": "",
  "A teacher asks students to imagine that all of Earth's history is compressed into a single 24-hour clock starting at midnight. Complex animal life does not appear until about 9:00 PM, dinosaurs go extinct at 11:39 PM, and all of recorded human history fits into the last fraction of a second before midnight. What concept is this exercise designed to illustrate?": "",
  "The immense span of the Precambrian and how recent complex life and especially human civilization are in the context of Earth's 4.6-billion-year history": "",
  "That humans have been on Earth for about half of its history": "",
  "That dinosaurs lived for most of Earth's history": "",
  "That the geologic time scale is not very long": "",
  "This clock analogy powerfully demonstrates that the Precambrian occupies the vast majority of Earth's history, complex life is relatively recent, and human civilization represents an almost immeasurably tiny sliver of geologic time.": "",
  "A student is examining a chart of the geologic time scale and notices that the Precambrian takes up most of the chart's length, but the Cenozoic Era, which includes the present day, is a very thin sliver at the top. The student asks why so little detail is shown for the Precambrian compared to more recent eras. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Scientists have not studied the Precambrian at all": "",
  "The Precambrian was actually very short but is drawn large for emphasis": "",
  "Precambrian rocks are rare and contain few complex fossils, making it harder to subdivide, while recent eras have abundant, diverse fossils allowing detailed divisions": "",
  "Nothing interesting happened during the Precambrian": "",
  "Precambrian life was mostly microscopic and soft-bodied, leaving few distinctive fossils for subdivision, while Phanerozoic rocks contain abundant, diverse fossils that allow geologists to define many detailed periods and epochs.": "",
  "A museum display shows that trilobites are found in Paleozoic rocks, dinosaur bones appear in Mesozoic rocks, and mammoth fossils are found in Cenozoic deposits. A visitor asks why these organisms are never found in the wrong era. What principle of the geologic time scale does this demonstrate?": "",
  "All organisms existed simultaneously but were buried in different layers by a single event": "",
  "Faunal succession: organisms appear and disappear in a predictable order in the rock record, reflecting evolutionary change and mass extinctions that define era boundaries": "",
  "Fossils are randomly distributed throughout all rock layers": "",
  "Scientists only look for certain fossils in certain rocks": "",
  "Faunal succession means that fossil species appear in a definite, predictable order reflecting evolutionary changes over time, with mass extinctions creating sharp boundaries where one set of organisms disappears and new ones evolve to take their place.": "",
  "Scientists studying Precambrian rocks in Australia discover layered mound-like structures called stromatolites, which are created by photosynthetic cyanobacteria. These are among the oldest evidence of life on Earth, dating back 3.5 billion years. What is the significance of these organisms for Earth's history?": "",
  "Cyanobacteria were among the first life forms and their photosynthesis gradually oxygenated Earth's atmosphere, making complex life possible billions of years later": "",
  "They prove that complex animals existed during the Precambrian": "",
  "Stromatolites show that the Precambrian had no living organisms": "",
  "These structures were formed by geological processes, not living organisms": "",
  "Stromatolite-forming cyanobacteria were among Earth's earliest life forms and their photosynthesis produced oxygen as a waste product, gradually transforming the atmosphere from oxygen-free to oxygen-rich over billions of years, a prerequisite for complex animal life.": "",
  "A geologist is giving a lecture about the end of the Paleozoic Era. She explains that the end-Permian extinction eliminated approximately 96% of marine species and 70% of land species, making it the worst mass extinction in Earth's history. A student asks what caused this catastrophe. What is the current scientific understanding?": "",
  "An asteroid impact identical to the one that killed the dinosaurs when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "Massive volcanic eruptions (Siberian Traps) that released enormous amounts of CO2 and toxic gases, causing extreme global warming, ocean acidification, and oxygen depletion": "",
  "Rapid continental movement that crushed most habitats when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "A nearby supernova that irradiated Earth, particularly regarding ocean following the established framework": "",
  "The end-Permian extinction is linked to the Siberian Traps, massive volcanic eruptions that released enormous quantities of greenhouse gases and toxic compounds, triggering severe global warming, ocean acidification, and widespread anoxia.": "",
  "During a class debate, one student argues that the Mesozoic Era should be called the 'Age of Dinosaurs,' but another points out that many other important groups also thrived during this time. Which of the following organisms also first appeared or diversified significantly during the Mesozoic?": "",
  "Only trilobites and early fish": "",
  "Only bacteria and single-celled organisms": "",
  "Flowering plants, early mammals, and birds all appeared or diversified during the Mesozoic alongside dinosaurs": "",
  "Modern humans evolved during the Mesozoic": "",
  "While dinosaurs dominated, the Mesozoic also saw the first appearance of flowering plants (angiosperms), the evolution of birds from theropod dinosaurs, and the diversification of early mammals that would later rise to prominence.": "",
  "A paleontologist finds a rock layer containing both ammonite fossils (which went extinct at the end of the Cretaceous, 66 million years ago) and no mammal fossils larger than a rat. Based on the geologic time scale, when was this rock layer most likely deposited?": "",
  "During the Paleozoic Era, when trilobites were dominant": "",
  "During the Precambrian, before complex life existed": "",
  "During the Mesozoic Era, when ammonites thrived and mammals were small and overshadowed by dinosaurs": "",
  "During the Cenozoic Era, after the dinosaur extinction": "",
  "Ammonites were abundant marine organisms during the Mesozoic, and mammals during this era were predominantly small, nocturnal creatures living in the shadow of dinosaurs, so the combination of these fossils indicates a Mesozoic age.": "",
  "Some scientists have proposed that we are now living in a new geological epoch called the 'Anthropocene,' defined by human impact on Earth systems. A skeptical student asks what evidence would support defining a new epoch. What kind of evidence would future geologists find in the rock record to mark this proposed boundary?": "",
  "A layer of volcanic ash from human-caused eruptions": "",
  "Only buildings and roads buried in sediment": "",
  "Future geologists would find no evidence because humans have not changed the planet significantly": "",
  "A distinct layer containing plastic particles, radioactive fallout from nuclear tests, elevated CO2 in ice cores, and a spike in species extinctions": "",
  "The proposed Anthropocene boundary would be marked by distinctive signatures in the geological record including microplastics, radioactive isotopes from nuclear testing, elevated atmospheric CO2, concrete and asphalt layers, and a dramatic increase in extinction rates.": "",
  "A high school student studying the geologic time scale notices that the three periods of the Mesozoic Era (Triassic, Jurassic, Cretaceous) each end with an extinction event, but only the end-Cretaceous one is as famous as the end-Permian. The student wonders what ended the Triassic Period. What caused the end-Triassic extinction?": "",
  "A collision between Earth and the Moon": "",
  "An asteroid impact similar to the Chicxulub event": "",
  "Massive volcanic eruptions associated with the breakup of Pangaea, which released greenhouse gases and caused climate disruption": "",
  "A global ice age that froze most of the planet": "",
  "The end-Triassic extinction approximately 201 million years ago is linked to the Central Atlantic Magmatic Province volcanism associated with the initial breakup of Pangaea, which released massive amounts of CO2 and caused severe climate change.": "",
  "A documentary filmmaker wants to create a movie showing the entire history of Earth in one hour. She asks a geologist how to allocate the time accurately. If each minute represents approximately 76.7 million years, how much screen time should the dinosaurs get (they lived from about 230 to 66 million years ago)?": "",
  "About 30 minutes, since dinosaurs dominated most of Earth's history": "",
  "About 2 minutes, since their 164-million-year reign represents a relatively small fraction of Earth's 4.6-billion-year history": "",
  "About 50 minutes, since most of the film should focus on dinosaurs": "",
  "About 10 minutes, since dinosaurs were the most important organisms": "",
  "Dinosaurs existed for approximately 164 million years (230 to 66 Ma), which divided by 76.7 million years per minute gives roughly 2 minutes of screen time, illustrating how even the long reign of dinosaurs is a small fraction of Earth's total history.": ""
}